# Animation and Motion Best Practices

## Accessibility first

- **Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`**: Use `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` to turn off or simplify non-essential animations when the user has asked the OS to reduce motion (vestibular issues, ADHD, etc.).
- **Avoid rapid flashing**: WCAG says no more than 3 flashes per second; avoid fast light/dark flicker (photosensitive epilepsy). Use [PEAT](https://trace.umd.edu/peat/) for content with flashing.
- **Non-essential motion**: If the animation isn’t needed to understand the content, consider disabling it by default or providing a pause/stop/hide control (WCAG: auto-playing motion &gt; 5s should be controllable).

## CSS approach

- **Progressive enhancement**: Prefer a static or reduced-motion default; add full motion only when safe and useful.
- **Disable cleanly**: Under reduced motion, set `animation: none` and `transition: none` (or a very short transition) so the layout doesn’t depend on the animation.

```css
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  .my-animated-thing {
    animation: none;
    transition-duration: 0.01ms;
  }
}
```

## When you need a library

- **GSAP**: Industry standard for high-end, corporate-style motion (EA, Google, Nike, etc.). ScrollTrigger for scroll reveals, timelines for hero staggers, robust easing and performance. See `.cursor/rules/gsap-animations.mdc` for patterns. Check [gsap.com/licensing](https://gsap.com/licensing/) for commercial use.
- **Motion** ([motion.dev](https://motion.dev)): MIT-licensed alternative; great for React/Vue and smaller bundles.
- **CSS-only**: Use `@keyframes` and `transition` for simple effects; keep animations in CSS and respect `prefers-reduced-motion` in the same stylesheet.

## Summary

Prefer minimal, purposeful motion; always respect `prefers-reduced-motion`; avoid rapid flashing; add a library (e.g. Motion) when you need complex or orchestrated animations.
